{"title_page": "Dusty Grave", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Dusty Grave\n| image            = Dustan Sheehan.jpg\n| background       = solo_singer\n| origin           = [[Santa Cruz, California]], U.S.\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[punk rock]]\n* [[psychobilly]]\n* [[horror punk]]\n* [[rockabilly]]\n* [[metal music|metal]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n}}\n| instruments      = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* guitar\n* bass\n\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Stellar Corpses]]\n* [[BAT!]]\n}}\n| website          =\n}}\n'''Dusty Grave''' is an American musician who is the lead singer, songwriter and founder of [[Stellar Corpses]].\n\n== Biography ==\nDusty grew up in [[Santa Cruz, California]] playing in various [[punk rock]], [[Metal (music genre)|metal]] and [[rockabilly]] bands. As a teen he worked at a FedEx Office in order to get cheap access to band flyers. There he also learned web and graphic design which he now does for a living in addition to playing music.\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Stellar Corpses ===\nDusty founded Stellar Corpses in 2005. He came up with the band name which is an astronomy term for a dead star as well as the logo while in college pursuing a degree in psychology.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://rockmusicreport.com/stellar-corpses-debut-album-dead-stars-drive-in-available-now-from-santa-carla-records/|title=Stellar Corpses Debut Album 'Dead Stars Drive-In' Available Now From Santa Carla Records|last=Media|first=CO5|website=Rock Music Report|language=en|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> Much of the band's aesthetic is based around [[The Lost Boys]] film.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nBetween 2005 and 2016 Stellar Corpses released their Respect the Dead EP (2007) and two full length albums: Welcome to the Nightmare (2009) and Dead Stars Drive-In (2012) along with extensive touring throughout Europe, USA and Mexico.\n\nDead Stars Drive-In (2012) featured several notable guest musicians including [[Hunter Burgan]] ([[AFI (band)|AFI]]), [[Jade Puget]] (AFI, [[Blaqk Audio|Black Audio]]), [[Mike Fasano (musician)|Mike Fasano]] ([[Tiger Army]]) and Michael Graves (formerly of the [[Misfits (band)|Misfits]]). The album was produced and engineered by Joe McGrath ([[Alkaline Trio]], [[Morrissey]], [[Green Day]], [[B.B. King]], [[The Offspring]]).<ref name=\"auto\">{{Citation|title=Dusty Grave & Eric Blair talk Stellar Corpses & his life in music 2019|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DIiX7TusvBs|language=en|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> The lead single from the album \"Vampire Kiss\" debuted at No. 9 on the alternative music charts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://goodtimes.sc/santa-cruz-arts-entertainment/santa-cruz-music/dead-men-rocking/|title=Dead Men Rocking|last=Orion|first=Damon|date=2012-02-01|website=Good Times Santa Cruz|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref>\n\nIn Aug 2017 Stellar Corpses was signed to [[Atomic Music Group]], one of the biggest talent booking agencies in the United States.\n\nIn 2019 Stellar Corpses members resigned due to demanding tour schedule,<ref name=\"auto\"/> leaving Dusty as the sole original member. New members include Sky Vaughan-Jayne ([[Son of Sam (band)|Son of Sam]], [[The Chelsea Smiles]]) on guitar and backing vocals, Maniacal Maniacal from Rezurex on bass, Jack Cash on guitar and Todd Bowen on drums. Stellar Corpses toured with the new lineup in Fall 2019 along with Calabrese and Nekromantix.\n\n=== Batcave Records ===\nIn 2016 Dusty moved to [[Los Angeles]] where he founded Batcave Records. He started the label as a way to promote the underground music scene.<ref name=\"auto\"/> He announced the label along with acoustic performances in the original Bat Cave in Griffith Park.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rocknloadmag.com/news/bat-unveils-first-single-via-dread-central-debut-album-bat-music-for-bat-people/|title=BAT! Unveils First Single via Dread Central; Debut Album \u2018Bat Music for Bat People\u2019|date=2019-04-15|website=R   o   c   k    'N'    L   o   a  d|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> The first Batcave Records release was Stellar Corpses Hellbound Heart EP.\n\nIn August 2019, Batcave Records and Cleopatra Records signed a partnership deal for future Batcave Records releases.\n\n=== BAT! ===\nIn April 2018 Dusty co-founded [[BAT!]] which was offered a record deal by [[Cleopatra Records]] after their first show. BAT! includes Dusty as well as Rene Delamuerte from Nekromantix / The Brains and Daniel deLeon from Rezurex. BAT! has been described as \"reminiscent of The Damned, The Cramps and the Stray Cats, they often enlist the help of fetish models and Dominatrixes to punish evildoers on stage.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/292397/exclusive-music-premiere-hear-revenge-of-the-batmask-by-burlesque-bondage-infused-bat/|title=Exclusive Music Premiere: Hear \"Revenge of the Batmask\" by Burlesque/Bondage infused BAT!|last=Millican|first=Josh|date=2019-04-10|website=Dread Central|language=en|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref>\n\nIn May 10, 2019 BAT!'s first Album Bat Music For Bat People was released on Cleopatra Records in association with Batcave Records. They toured in Europe and the US playing lead guitar for Rezurex in support of Nekromantix.\n\n== Personal life ==\n*\n\nDusty has talked openly about his struggles with alcohol and drug addiction. He first got sober in 2004 but relapsed during Stellar Corpses first tour in 2007. He later crashed and totaled his car while drunk driving with police saying he should\u2019ve died. He went to jail for the 13th time. In September 2009 he got sober and has remained drug and alcohol free.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nDusty is also a vegan.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grave, Dusty}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American punk rock singers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Santa Cruz, California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Dusty Grave\n| image            = Dustan Sheehan.jpg\n| background       = solo_singer\n| origin           = [[Santa Cruz, California]], U.S.\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[punk rock]]\n* [[psychobilly]]\n* [[horror punk]]\n* [[rockabilly]]\n* [[metal music|metal]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n}}\n| instruments      = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* guitar\n* bass\n\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Stellar Corpses]]\n* [[BAT!]]\n}}\n| website          =\n}}\n'''Dusty Grave''' is an American musician who is the lead singer, songwriter and founder of [[Stellar Corpses]].\n\n== Biography ==\nDusty grew up in [[Santa Cruz, California]] playing in various [[punk rock]], [[Metal (music genre)|metal]] and [[rockabilly]] bands. As a teen he worked at a FedEx Office in order to get cheap access to band flyers. There he also learned web and graphic design which he now does for a living in addition to playing music.\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Stellar Corpses ===\nDusty founded Stellar Corpses in 2005. He came up with the band name which is an astronomy term for a dead star as well as the logo while in college pursuing a degree in psychology.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://rockmusicreport.com/stellar-corpses-debut-album-dead-stars-drive-in-available-now-from-santa-carla-records/|title=Stellar Corpses Debut Album 'Dead Stars Drive-In' Available Now From Santa Carla Records|last=Media|first=CO5|website=Rock Music Report|language=en|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> Much of the band's aesthetic is based around [[The Lost Boys]] film.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nBetween 2005 and 2016 Stellar Corpses released their Respect the Dead EP (2007) and two full length albums: Welcome to the Nightmare (2009) and Dead Stars Drive-In (2012) along with extensive touring throughout Europe, USA and Mexico.\n\nDead Stars Drive-In (2012) featured several notable guest musicians including [[Hunter Burgan]] ([[AFI (band)|AFI]]), [[Jade Puget]] (AFI, [[Blaqk Audio|Black Audio]]), [[Mike Fasano]] ([[Tiger Army]]) and Michael Graves (formerly of the [[Misfits (band)|Misfits]]). The album was produced and engineered by Joe McGrath ([[Alkaline Trio]], [[Morrissey]], [[Green Day]], [[B.B. King]], [[The Offspring]]).<ref name=\"auto\">{{Citation|title=Dusty Grave & Eric Blair talk Stellar Corpses & his life in music 2019|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DIiX7TusvBs|language=en|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> The lead single from the album \"Vampire Kiss\" debuted at No. 9 on the alternative music charts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://goodtimes.sc/santa-cruz-arts-entertainment/santa-cruz-music/dead-men-rocking/|title=Dead Men Rocking|last=Orion|first=Damon|date=2012-02-01|website=Good Times Santa Cruz|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref>\n\nIn Aug 2017 Stellar Corpses was signed to [[Atomic Music Group]], one of the biggest talent booking agencies in the United States.\n\nIn 2019 Stellar Corpses members resigned due to demanding tour schedule,<ref name=\"auto\"/> leaving Dusty as the sole original member. New members include Sky Vaughan-Jayne ([[Son of Sam (band)|Son of Sam]], [[The Chelsea Smiles]]) on guitar and backing vocals, Maniacal Maniacal from Rezurex on bass, Jack Cash on guitar and Todd Bowen on drums. Stellar Corpses toured with the new lineup in Fall 2019 along with Calabrese and Nekromantix.\n\n=== Batcave Records ===\nIn 2016 Dusty moved to [[Los Angeles]] where he founded Batcave Records. He started the label as a way to promote the underground music scene.<ref name=\"auto\"/> He announced the label along with acoustic performances in the original Bat Cave in Griffith Park.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rocknloadmag.com/news/bat-unveils-first-single-via-dread-central-debut-album-bat-music-for-bat-people/|title=BAT! Unveils First Single via Dread Central; Debut Album \u2018Bat Music for Bat People\u2019|date=2019-04-15|website=R   o   c   k    'N'    L   o   a  d|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> The first Batcave Records release was Stellar Corpses Hellbound Heart EP.\n\nIn August 2019, Batcave Records and Cleopatra Records signed a partnership deal for future Batcave Records releases.\n\n=== BAT! ===\nIn April 2018 Dusty co-founded [[BAT!]] which was offered a record deal by [[Cleopatra Records]] after their first show. BAT! includes Dusty as well as Rene Delamuerte from Nekromantix / The Brains and Daniel deLeon from Rezurex. BAT! has been described as \"reminiscent of The Damned, The Cramps and the Stray Cats, they often enlist the help of fetish models and Dominatrixes to punish evildoers on stage.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dreadcentral.com/news/292397/exclusive-music-premiere-hear-revenge-of-the-batmask-by-burlesque-bondage-infused-bat/|title=Exclusive Music Premiere: Hear \"Revenge of the Batmask\" by Burlesque/Bondage infused BAT!|last=Millican|first=Josh|date=2019-04-10|website=Dread Central|language=en|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref>\n\nIn May 10, 2019 BAT!'s first Album Bat Music For Bat People was released on Cleopatra Records in association with Batcave Records. They toured in Europe and the US playing lead guitar for Rezurex in support of Nekromantix.\n\n== Personal life ==\n*\n\nDusty has talked openly about his struggles with alcohol and drug addiction. He first got sober in 2004 but relapsed during Stellar Corpses first tour in 2007. He later crashed and totaled his car while drunk driving with police saying he should\u2019ve died. He went to jail for the 13th time. In September 2009 he got sober and has remained drug and alcohol free.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nDusty is also a vegan.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grave, Dusty}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American punk rock singers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Santa Cruz, California]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - fix links -Mike Fasano", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dusty_Grave"}
{"title_page": "Robert W. Kenny", "text_new": "[[File:Robert W. Kenny.jpg|thumb|right|Robert W. Kenny (undated), 21st Attorney General of [[California]] (1943-1947).]]\n'''Robert W. Kenny''' (August 21, 1901 &ndash; July 20, 1976), 21st Attorney General of [[California]] (1943-1947), was \"a colorful figure in state politics for many years\" who in 1946 ran unsuccessfully against [[Earl Warren]] for state governor (a race in which Warren won both Republican and Democratic nominations).  In 1947, he led the defense of the [[Hollywood Ten]] while becoming Dean of [[Brown University]] (1947-1952).<ref name=NYTobit>\n{{cite news\n| first = Alfred E. \n| last = Clark\n| title = Robert Kenny, Attorney, Dead; Led National Lawyers Guild\n| newspaper = New York Time\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1976/07/22/archives/robert-kenny-attorney-dead-led-national-lawyers-guild.html\n| page = 34\n| date = 22 July 1976\n| accessdate = 18 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=Brown>\n{{cite encyclopedia\n| editor = Martha Mitchell \n| article = Dean\n| title = Encyclopedia Brunoniana\n| publisher = Brown University\n| url = https://www.brown.edu/Administration/News_Bureau/Databases/Encyclopedia/search.php?serial=D0060\n| date = 22 July 1976\n| accessdate = 18 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=OAC-Kenny>\n{{cite web \n| title = Register of the Robert W. Kenny Papers, 1823-1975 - Biography\n| url = https://oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/tf3199n6b1/admin/#bioghist-1.7.3\n| publisher = Online Archive of California\n| date = \n| accessdate = 22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nRobert Walker Kenny was born on August 21, 1901, in [[Los Angeles, California]]. His mother was Minnie Summerfield.  His father, Robert Wolfenden Kenny (1863-1914) was a successful [[banker]] and civic leader in Los Angeles and [[Berkeley, California|Berkeley]], [[California]]. Kenny's grandfather, George L. Kenny, arrived in [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]] in the early 1850s with his friends, the brothers A.L. Bancroft and [[Hubert Howe Bancroft]]. The three men formed a partnership and established the first bookstore in San Francisco.<ref name=\"Kenny\"/>  In 1921, Kenny graduated at 18 from [[Stanford University]].<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=OAC-Kenny/>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Press===\n[[File:JamesRolphJr.jpg|thumb|right|Kenny rose to power on the coattails of [[James Rolph]] by supporting him for California governor in 1930]]\nIn 1921, Kenny joined the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', where he worked with [[Chapin Hall]], and eventually became a financial editor there.  In 1922, he joined [[United Press]] news service.  He then worked for the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' in Paris.  In 1923, he returned to Los Angeles and worked for ''United News''.  He then opened his own press service with Ted Taylor, called the Los Angeles Press Service, while also working the for the ''[[Los Angeles Express]]''.  After studying law privately, in 1926 he passed a civil service examination and was admitted to the state bar.<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=OAC-Kenny/>\n\n===California government service===\n\nIn 1927, Kenny began working in the [[Los Angeles County]] counsel's office as \"Deputy of the County Counsel.\"<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=OAC-Kenny/>  In 1929, he joined the state legislature.<ref name=OAC-Kenny/>  In 1930, Kenny supported [[James Rolph]] Jr., who became California governor, and received an appointment as judge to the Los Angeles Municipal Court, followed by promotion to the Los Angeles Superior Court.<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=OAC-Kenny/>  In 1934, he won an election and became municipal judge for small claims court.<ref name=OAC-Kenny/>  He then became a judge in the law and motion court.<ref name=OAC-Kenny/>\nAt some time in the 1930s, Kenny became a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]].<ref name=NYTobit/>  He was an early advocate for [[civil rights]] in California. He restructured the [[California Department of Justice]] (DOJ) to be similar to the [[United States Department of Justice]]; for example, he transferred the California DOJ main office from [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]] closer to the state legislature in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]], and created [[civil service]] positions instead of political appointments within the California DOJ. He also was instrumental in abolishing the legal existence of the [[Ku Klux Klan]] in California.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nKenny also served as a Municipal Court Judge and later a [[Los Angeles County Superior Court|Superior Court]] Judge in [[Los Angeles, California]]. He served in the [[California State Senate]] from 1939\u20131943. \n\n===Private practice===\n[[File:Wendell L. Willkie on the cover of TIME Magazine, July 31, 1939.jpg|thumb|right|[[Wendell Willkie]] (here, on the cover of [[TIME Magazine|''Time'' magazine]], July 31, 1939) helped Kenny win his case for [[CPUSA]] leader [[William Schneideman]] in 1943]]\nKenny resigned his judgeship.  In 1939, he dissolved a law partnership with Paul Vallee and Lawrence Beilensen.  He set up a new partnership with Morris E. Cohen, which lasted until 1948.  [[Robert O. Curran]] joined the firm but left to fight in [[World War II]]; Robert S. Morris replaced him.<ref name=OAC-Kenny/>  \n\nClients included [[William Schneiderman]], head of the California section of the [[Communist Party USA]]; Kenny helped him with citizenship papers in 1940, a case he lost but which [[Wendell Willkie]] helped win on appeal in 1943.<ref name=OAC-Kenny/>\n\n===Attorney General of California===\n[[File:Earl Warren Portrait, half figure, seated, facing front, as Governor.jpg|thumb|upright|Kenny lost to [[Earl Warren]] for Governor of California in 1946]]\nIn 1942, Kenny was elected [[Attorney General]] of California, beating [[Louis H. Burke]], and served one term to 1947.<ref name=OAC-Kenny/><ref name=Kenny>{{cite web|title=Guide to the Robert Walker Kenny Papers, 1920-1947|url=http://www.oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/tf2r29n6db/|publisher=The Regents of The University of California|accessdate=26 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1946, Kenny sought the Democratic nomination for Governor, but was defeated by [[Earl Warren]].  Although Warren was a Republican, California law at that time permitted a candidate to run in both primaries, a practice known as [[cross-filing]].  Warren also won the Republican nomination that year and went on to score an easy general election victory.<ref name=OAC-Kenny/><ref>{{cite book|last=Gunther|first=John|authorlink=John Gunther|title=[[Inside U.S.A. (book)|Inside U.S.A.]]|pages=18\u201319|location=[[New York City|New York]], [[London]]|publisher=[[Harper & Brothers]]|year=1947}}</ref>\n\n===NLG, Hollywood Ten, and HUAC===\n[[File:Hollywood10.jpg|thumb|right|Kenny was lead lawyer for the [[Hollywood Ten]] and appeared here front and center on November 1947 as they await fingerprinting at the [[U.S. Marshal]]'s office after citations for [[contempt of Congress]]. Front row (from left): [[Herbert Biberman]], attorneys [[Martin Popper]] and [[Robert W. Kenny]], [[Albert Maltz]], [[Lester Cole]]. Middle row: [[Dalton Trumbo]], [[John Howard Lawson]], [[Alvah Bessie]], [[Samuel Ornitz]]. Back row: [[Ring Lardner Jr.]], [[Edward Dmytryk]], [[Adrian Scott]].]]\nIn 1937, he supported [[Franklin Delano Roosevelt]]'s attempt at \"court-packing\" of the [[United States Supreme Court]] in FDR's [[Judicial Procedures Reform Bill of 1937]].<ref name=NYTobit/>  \"Out of that battle grew the [[National Lawyers Guild]]\" (NLG), wrote the ''[[New York Times]]'' in 1976 at Kenny's death.<ref name=NYTobit/>  On February 22, 1937, when the NLG formed, Kenny was a founding member.<ref name=OAC-Kenny/>  In 1940, Kenny became national resident of the NLG through 1948.<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=OAC-Kenny/> As NLG state president, he became involved in the aftermath of the [[Zoot Suit Riots]].<ref name=\"Kenney\">[https://archive.org/stream/myfirstfortyyear00kenn/myfirstfortyyear00kenn_djvu.txt My first forty years in California politics, 1922-1962 oral history transcript] Robert W. Kenny</ref><ref>[http://www.joincalifornia.com/candidate/154 Robert W. Kenny-JoinCalifornia.com]</ref>\n\nIn 1946, Kenny returned to private practice.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nKenny served as lead counsel with [[Bartley Crum]]<ref name=LastParty>\n{{cite news\n  | title = The Last Party\n  | newspaper = New York Times\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1997/04/27/books/the-last-party.html\n  | date = 27 April 1997\n  | accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref> and [https://heinonline.org/HOL/LandingPage?handle=hein.journals/guild56&div=12&id=&page= Benjamin Margolis]<ref>\n{{cite news\n| url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/2005/04/05/john-mcternan-dies/08d886bd-7f11-442b-b75b-9cb4a0926f3d/\n| newspaper = Washington Post\n| title = John McTernan Dies\n| date = 5 April 2005\n| accessdate = 1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite journal\n| url = https://heinonline.org/HOL/LandingPage?handle=hein.journals/guild56&div=12&id=&page=\n| journal = Guild Practice\n| publisher = National Lawyers Guild\n| title = Ben Margolis: A Lifetime of Contempt for Injustice and Oppression \n| date = 1999\n| accessdate = 1 April 2020}}</ref> to the \"Unfriendly Nineteen\" subpoenaed to testify before the [[House Un-American Activities Committee]] (HUAC) in October 1947.  Only ten people wound up testifying, all cited for contempt of Congress, and so became the [[Hollywood Ten]].<ref name=OAC-Kenny/>\n\n===Later life===\n[[File:Judy Garland and Fletcher Bowron.jpg|thumb|right|In 1950, Kenny lost the mayorship of Los Angeles to [[Fletcher Bowron]] (here with [[Judy Garland]] in 1952)]]\nIn 1947, Kenny became became Dean of Students at [[Brown University]] through 1952.<ref name=Brown/><ref>\n{{cite book\n| title = Educational Directory:  Federal and State School Officers\n| publisher = Federal Security Agency\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=c5ItllCi808C\n| pages = 110\n| date = 1947\n| accessdate = 22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1948, Kenny and Robert S. Morris formed a new law partnership.  In the 1940s and 1950s, they represented \"many people under indictment for questionable activities.\"<ref name=OAC-Kenny/>  Clients included [[Luisa Moreno Bemis]], Guatamalan labor activist, many \"unfriendly\" witnesses (including the Hollywood Ten) before HUAC in Los Angeles in 1952, as well as musicians before HUAC in 1956. Kenny was a member of the [[American Committee for the Protection of Foreign Born]].  Partner Robert S. Morris was a member of the Immigration and Deportation Committee in the Los Angeles chapter of the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU).<ref name=OAC-Kenny/>\n\nIn 1950, Kenny ran for California state senator against Glenn Anderson and [[Jack Tenney]] for the Democratic nomination; Tenney won.  The same year, he ran for Los Angles mayor; [[Fletcher Bowron]] won in a recall.<ref name=OAC-Kenny/>\n\nIn 1957, he was one of the lawyers who helped 23 Hollywood screen writers and actors win a Supreme Court review of their challenge of the [[Hollywood blacklist]].<ref name=NYTobit/>\n[[File:Alexander Meiklejohn Time magazine cover, October 1, 1928.jpg|thumb|right|Kenny served on the board of the [[Defending Dissent Foundation|NCA-HUAC]] with other First Amendment defenders including [[Alexander Meiklejohn]] (here, on cover ''Time'' in 1928)]]\nIn 1960, Kenny was treasurer of the National Committee to Abolish the [[House Un-American Activities Committee]] ([[Defending Dissent Foundation|NCA-HUAC]]), whose members included:  \n* Honorary Chairmen:  James Imbrie, [[Alexander Meiklejohn]], [[Clarence Pickett]]\n* Chairman Emeritus: [[Aubrey Willis Williams]]\n* Chairman: [[Harvey O'Connor]]\n* Vice Chairman: [[Dorothy Marshall]], Sylvia Crane, Charles Jackson, Harry Bernard, Reverence Edward L. Peat\n* Southern Regional Committee:  Carl Braden, John Lewis, Reverend C.T. Vivian, Reverence Wyatt T. Walker\n* Secretary:  Professor Walter S. Vince\n* Treasurer:  Robert W. Kenny\n* Executive Director:  [[Frank Wilkinson]]<ref>\n{{cite book\n| title = Journal of the Senate, Legislature of the State of California\n| publisher = California State Printing Office\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=c5ItllCi808C\n| pages = 93 (members), 114 (petition)\n| date = 1970\n| accessdate = 22 April 2020}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = National Committee to Abolish the House Un-American Activities Committee\n| publisher = Library of Congress\n| url = http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n88609710.html\n| date = 1992-10-07\n| accessdate = 22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966, California Governor [[Edmund G. Brown]] appointed Kenny again a state judge.  In 1975, he retired from the bench.<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=OAC-Kenny/>\n\n==Personal life and death==\n\nIn 1922, Kenny married Sara McCann; she died in 1966.<ref name=OAC-Kenny/>\n\nIn the 1930s, Kenny was a \"liberal Republican.\"<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nRobert Walter Kenny died age 74 on July 20, 1976, at Scripps Memorial Hospital in [[La Jolla, California]] with no survivors.<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=OAC-Kenny/>\n\n==Works==\n\n* ''The Law of Freedom in a Platform'' by Gerrard Winstanley, edited by Robert W. Kenny (1973)<ref>\n{{cite book\n| editor = Robert W. Kenny\n| first = Gerrard \n| last = Winstanley\n| title = The Law of Freedom in a Platform\n| publisher = Schocken Books\n| url = https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/american-political-science-review/article/law-of-freedom-in-a-platform-by-gerrard-winstanley-edited-by-robert-w-kenny-new-york-schocken-books-1973-pp-160-1200-cloth-295-paper/A4177D7F8DA4863140D7D5ABDC674395\n| date = 1973\n| pages = 160\n| accessdate = 22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[California Attorney General]]\n* [[National Lawyers Guild]]\n* [[Hollywood blacklist]]\n* [[Hollywood Ten]]\n* [[Bartley Crum]]\n* [[Benjamin Margolis]]\n* [[William Schneiderman]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.criticalpast.com/video/65675026586_HUAC-hearing_attorneys-Robert-Kenny-and-Bartley-Crum-appeal Critical Past - Kenny and Crum ask HUAC to stop hearings (1947)]\n*[http://www.oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/tf2r29n6db/ Guide to the Robert Walker Kenny Papers] at [[The Bancroft Library]]\n*[http://ag.ca.gov/ag/history/21kenny.php Kenny biography] from  State of California Department of Justice Office of the Attorney General\n*[http://www.oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/tf2r29n6db/ Robert Walker Kenny Papers], [[Bancroft Library|The Bancroft Library]]\n* [https://dl.library.ucla.edu/islandora/object/edu.ucla.library.specialCollections.losAngelesDailyNews:1185 Photo of William E. MacFaden and Robert W. Kenny (1934)]\n* [https://scocal.stanford.edu/opinion/warner-v-kenny-29323 Stanford University]: Warner v. Kenny\n* [http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n80009886.html Library of Congress]:  Kenny, Robert W. (Robert Walker), 1901-1976\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-legal}}\n{{Succession box |\n  before= [[Earl Warren]]| |\n  title= [[California Attorney General]] |\n  years= 1943&ndash;1947 |\n  after= [[Frederick N. Howser]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Attorneys General of California}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kenny, Robert W}}\n[[Category:California state senators]]\n[[Category:California state court judges]]\n[[Category:California Attorneys General]]\n[[Category:1901 births]]\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American judges]]\n\n{{California-politician-stub}}\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Robert W. Kenny.jpg|thumb|right|Robert W. Kenny (undated), 21st Attorney General of [[California]] (1943-1947).]]\n'''Robert W. Kenny''' (August 21, 1901 &ndash; July 20, 1976), 21st Attorney General of [[California]] (1943-1947), was \"a colorful figure in state politics for many years\" who in 1946 ran unsuccessfully against [[Earl Warren]] for state governor (a race in which Warren won both Republican and Democratic nominations).  In 1947, he led the defense of the [[Hollywood Ten]] while becoming Dean of [[Brown University]] (1947-1952).<ref name=NYTobit>\n{{cite news\n| first = Alfred E. \n| last = Clark\n| title = Robert Kenny, Attorney, Dead; Led National Lawyers Guild\n| newspaper = New York Time\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/1976/07/22/archives/robert-kenny-attorney-dead-led-national-lawyers-guild.html\n| page = 34\n| date = 22 July 1976\n| accessdate = 18 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=Brown>\n{{cite encyclopedia\n| editor = Martha Mitchell \n| article = Dean\n| title = Encyclopedia Brunoniana\n| publisher = Brown University\n| url = https://www.brown.edu/Administration/News_Bureau/Databases/Encyclopedia/search.php?serial=D0060\n| date = 22 July 1976\n| accessdate = 18 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=OAC-Kenny>\n{{cite web \n| title = Register of the Robert W. Kenny Papers, 1823-1975 - Biography\n| url = https://oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/tf3199n6b1/admin/#bioghist-1.7.3\n\n| publisher = Online Archive of California\n| date = \n| accessdate = 22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nRobert Walker Kenny was born on August 21, 1901, in [[Los Angeles, California]]. His mother was Minnie Summerfield.  His father, Robert Wolfenden Kenny (1863-1914) was a successful [[banker]] and civic leader in Los Angeles and [[Berkeley, California|Berkeley]], [[California]]. Kenny's grandfather, George L. Kenny, arrived in [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]] in the early 1850s with his friends, the brothers A.L. Bancroft and [[Hubert Howe Bancroft]]. The three men formed a partnership and established the first bookstore in San Francisco.<ref name=\"Kenny\"/>  In 1921, Kenny graduated at 18 from [[Stanford University]].<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=OAC-Kenny/>\n\n\n==Career==\n\n===Press===\n[[File:JamesRolphJr.jpg|thumb|right|Kenny rose to power on the coattails of [[James Rolph]] by supporting him for California governor in 1930]]\nIn 1921, Kenny joined the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', where he worked with [[Chapin Hall]], and eventually became a financial editor there.  In 1922, he joined [[United Press]] news service.  He then worked for the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' in Paris.  In 1923, he returned to Los Angeles and worked for ''United News''.  He then opened his own press service with Ted Taylor, called the Los Angeles Press Service, while also working the for the ''[[Los Angeles Express]]''.  After studying law privately, in 1926 he passed a civil service examination and was admitted to the state bar.<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=OAC-Kenny/>\n\n===California government service===\n\nIn 1927, Kenny began working in the [[Los Angeles County]] counsel's office as \"Deputy of the County Counsel.\"<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=OAC-Kenny/>  In 1929, he joined the state legislature.<ref name=OAC-Kenny/>  In 1930, Kenny supported [[James Rolph]] Jr., who became California governor, and received an appointment as judge to the Los Angeles Municipal Court, followed by promotion to the Los Angeles Superior Court.<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=OAC-Kenny/>  In 1934, he won an election and became municipal judge for small claims court.<ref name=OAC-Kenny/>  He then became a judge in the law and motion court.<ref name=OAC-Kenny/>\nAt some time in the 1930s, Kenny became a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]].<ref name=NYTobit/>  He was an early advocate for [[civil rights]] in California. He restructured the [[California Department of Justice]] (DOJ) to be similar to the [[United States Department of Justice]]; for example, he transferred the California DOJ main office from [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]] closer to the state legislature in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]], and created [[civil service]] positions instead of political appointments within the California DOJ. He also was instrumental in abolishing the legal existence of the [[Ku Klux Klan]] in California.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nKenny also served as a Municipal Court Judge and later a [[Los Angeles County Superior Court|Superior Court]] Judge in [[Los Angeles, California]]. He served in the [[California State Senate]] from 1939\u20131943. \n\n===Private practice===\n[[File:Wendell L. Willkie on the cover of TIME Magazine, July 31, 1939.jpg|thumb|right|[[Wendell Willkie]] (here, on the cover of [[TIME Magazine|''Time'' magazine]], July 31, 1939) helped Kenny win his case for [[CPUSA]] leader [[William Schneideman]] in 1943]]\nKenny resigned his judgeship.  In 1939, he dissolved a law partnership with Paul Vallee and Lawrence Beilensen.  He set up a new partnership with Morris E. Cohen, which lasted until 1948.  [[Robert O. Curran]] joined the firm but left to fight in [[World War II]]; Robert S. Morris replaced him.<ref name=OAC-Kenny/>  \n\nClients included [[William Schneiderman]], head of the California section of the [[Communist Party USA]]; Kenny helped him with citizenship papers in 1940, a case he lost but which [[Wendell Willkie]] helped win on appeal in 1943.<ref name=OAC-Kenny/>\n\n===Attorney General of California===\n[[File:Earl Warren Portrait, half figure, seated, facing front, as Governor.jpg|thumb|upright|Kenny lost to [[Earl Warren]] for Governor of California in 1946]]\nIn 1942, Kenny was elected [[Attorney General]] of California, beating [[Louis H. Burke]], and served one term to 1947.<ref name=OAC-Kenny/><ref name=Kenny>{{cite web|title=Guide to the Robert Walker Kenny Papers, 1920-1947|url=http://www.oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/tf2r29n6db/|publisher=The Regents of The University of California|accessdate=26 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 1946, Kenny sought the Democratic nomination for Governor, but was defeated by [[Earl Warren]].  Although Warren was a Republican, California law at that time permitted a candidate to run in both primaries, a practice known as [[cross-filing]].  Warren also won the Republican nomination that year and went on to score an easy general election victory.<ref name=OAC-Kenny/><ref>{{cite book|last=Gunther|first=John|authorlink=John Gunther|title=[[Inside U.S.A. (book)|Inside U.S.A.]]|pages=18\u201319|location=[[New York City|New York]], [[London]]|publisher=[[Harper & Brothers]]|year=1947}}</ref>\n\n===NLG, Hollywood Ten, and HUAC===\n[[File:Hollywood10.jpg|thumb|right|Kenny was lead lawyer for the [[Hollywood Ten]] and appeared here front and center on November 1947 as they await fingerprinting at the [[U.S. Marshal]]'s office after citations for [[contempt of Congress]]. Front row (from left): [[Herbert Biberman]], attorneys [[Martin Popper]] and [[Robert W. Kenny]], [[Albert Maltz]], [[Lester Cole]]. Middle row: [[Dalton Trumbo]], [[John Howard Lawson]], [[Alvah Bessie]], [[Samuel Ornitz]]. Back row: [[Ring Lardner Jr.]], [[Edward Dmytryk]], [[Adrian Scott]].]]\nIn 1937, he supported [[Franklin Delano Roosevelt]]'s attempt at \"court-packing\" of the [[United States Supreme Court]] in FDR's [[Judicial Procedures Reform Bill of 1937]].<ref name=NYTobit/>  \"Out of that battle grew the [[National Lawyers Guild]]\" (NLG), wrote the ''[[New York Times]]'' in 1976 at Kenny's death.<ref name=NYTobit/>  On February 22, 1937, when the NLG formed, Kenny was a founding member.<ref name=OAC-Kenny/>  In 1940, Kenny became national resident of the NLG through 1948.<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=OAC-Kenny/> As NLG state president, he became involved in the aftermath of the [[Zoot Suit Riots]].<ref name=\"Kenney\">[https://archive.org/stream/myfirstfortyyear00kenn/myfirstfortyyear00kenn_djvu.txt My first forty years in California politics, 1922-1962 oral history transcript] Robert W. Kenny</ref><ref>[http://www.joincalifornia.com/candidate/154 Robert W. Kenny-JoinCalifornia.com]</ref>\n\nIn 1946, Kenny returned to private practice.<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nKenny served as lead counsel with [[Bartley Crum]]<ref name=LastParty>\n{{cite news\n  | title = The Last Party\n  | newspaper = New York Times\n  | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1997/04/27/books/the-last-party.html\n  | date = 27 April 1997\n  | accessdate = 4 April 2020}}</ref> and [https://heinonline.org/HOL/LandingPage?handle=hein.journals/guild56&div=12&id=&page= Benjamin Margolis]<ref>\n{{cite news\n| url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/2005/04/05/john-mcternan-dies/08d886bd-7f11-442b-b75b-9cb4a0926f3d/\n| newspaper = Washington Post\n| title = John McTernan Dies\n| date = 5 April 2005\n| accessdate = 1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite journal\n| url = https://heinonline.org/HOL/LandingPage?handle=hein.journals/guild56&div=12&id=&page=\n| journal = Guild Practice\n| publisher = National Lawyers Guild\n| title = Ben Margolis: A Lifetime of Contempt for Injustice and Oppression \n| date = 1999\n| accessdate = 1 April 2020}}</ref> to the \"Unfriendly Nineteen\" subpoenaed to testify before the [[House Un-American Activities Committee]] (HUAC) in October 1947.  Only ten people wound up testifying, all cited for contempt of Congress, and so became the [[Hollywood Ten]].<ref name=OAC-Kenny/>\n\n===Later life===\n[[File:Judy Garland and Fletcher Bowron.jpg|thumb|right|In 1950, Kenny lost the mayorship of Los Angeles to [[Fletcher Bowron]] (here with [[Judy Garland]] in 1952)]]\nIn 1947, Kenny became became Dean of Students at [[Brown University]] through 1952.<ref name=Brown/><ref>\n{{cite book\n| title = Educational Directory:  Federal and State School Officers\n| publisher = Federal Security Agency\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=c5ItllCi808C\n| pages = 110\n| date = 1947\n| accessdate = 22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1948, Kenny and Robert S. Morris formed a new law partnership.  In the 1940s and 1950s, they represented \"many people under indictment for questionable activities.\"<ref name=OAC-Kenny/>  Clients included [[Luisa Moreno Bemis]], Guatamalan labor activist, many \"unfriendly\" witnesses (including the Hollywood Ten) before HUAC in Los Angeles in 1952, as well as musicians before HUAC in 1956. Kenny was a member of the [[American Committee for the Protection of Foreign Born]].  Partner Robert S. Morris was a member of the Immigration and Deportation Committee in the Los Angeles chapter of the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU).<ref name=OAC-Kenny/>\n\nIn 1950, Kenny ran for California state senator against Glenn Anderson and [[Jack Tenney]] for the Democratic nomination; Tenney won.  The same year, he ran for Los Angles mayor; [[Fletcher Bowron]] won in a recall.<ref name=OAC-Kenny/>\n\nIn 1957, he was one of the lawyers who helped 23 Hollywood screen writers and actors win a Supreme Court review of their challenge of the [[Hollywood blacklist]].<ref name=NYTobit/>\n[[File:Alexander Meiklejohn Time magazine cover, October 1, 1928.jpg|thumb|right|Kenny served on the board of the [[Defending Dissent Foundation|NCA-HUAC]] with other First Amendment defenders including [[Alexander Meiklejohn]] (here, on cover ''Time'' in 1928)]]\nIn 1960, Kenny was treasurer of the National Committee to Abolish the [[House Un-American Activities Committee]] ([[Defending Dissent Foundation|NCA-HUAC]]), whose members included:  \n* Honorary Chairmen:  James Imbrie, [[Alexander Meiklejohn]], [[Clarence Pickett]]\n* Chairman Emeritus: [[Aubrey Willis Williams]]\n* Chairman: [[Harvey O'Connor]]\n* Vice Chairman: [[Dorothy Marshall]], Sylvia Crane, Charles Jackson, Harry Bernard, Reverence Edward L. Peat\n* Southern Regional Committee:  Carl Braden, John Lewis, Reverend C.T. Vivian, Reverence Wyatt T. Walker\n* Secretary:  Professor Walter S. Vince\n* Treasurer:  Robert W. Kenny\n* Executive Director:  [[Frank Wilkinson]]<ref>\n{{cite book\n| title = Journal of the Senate, Legislature of the State of California\n| publisher = California State Printing Office\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=c5ItllCi808C\n| pages = 93 (members), 114 (petition)\n| date = 1970\n| accessdate = 22 April 2020}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n| title = National Committee to Abolish the House Un-American Activities Committee\n| publisher = Library of Congress\n| url = http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n88609710.html\n| date = 1992-10-07\n| accessdate = 22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1966, California Governor [[Edmund G. Brown]] appointed Kenny again a state judge.  In 1975, he retired from the bench.<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=OAC-Kenny/>\n\n==Personal life and death==\n\nIn 1922, Kenny married Sara McCann; she died in 1966.<ref name=OAC-Kenny/>\n\nIn the 1930s, Kenny was a \"liberal Republican.\"<ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nRobert Walter Kenny died age 74 on July 20, 1976, at Scripps Memorial Hospital in [[La Jolla, California]] with no survivors.<ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=OAC-Kenny/>\n\n==Works==\n\n* ''The Law of Freedom in a Platform'' by Gerrard Winstanley, edited by Robert W. Kenny (1973)<ref>\n{{cite book\n| editor = Robert W. Kenny\n| first = Gerrard \n| last = Winstanley\n| title = The Law of Freedom in a Platform\n| publisher = Schocken Books\n| url = https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/american-political-science-review/article/law-of-freedom-in-a-platform-by-gerrard-winstanley-edited-by-robert-w-kenny-new-york-schocken-books-1973-pp-160-1200-cloth-295-paper/A4177D7F8DA4863140D7D5ABDC674395\n| date = 1973\n| pages = 160\n| accessdate = 22 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[California Attorney General]]\n* [[National Lawyers Guild]]\n* [[Hollywood blacklist]]\n* [[Hollywood Ten]]\n* [[Bartley Crum]]\n* [[Benjamin Margolis]]\n* [[William Schneiderman]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.criticalpast.com/video/65675026586_HUAC-hearing_attorneys-Robert-Kenny-and-Bartley-Crum-appeal Critical Past - Kenny and Crum ask HUAC to stop hearings (1947)]\n*[http://www.oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/tf2r29n6db/ Guide to the Robert Walker Kenny Papers] at [[The Bancroft Library]]\n*[http://ag.ca.gov/ag/history/21kenny.php Kenny biography] from  State of California Department of Justice Office of the Attorney General\n*[http://www.oac.cdlib.org/findaid/ark:/13030/tf2r29n6db/ Robert Walker Kenny Papers], [[Bancroft Library|The Bancroft Library]]\n* [https://dl.library.ucla.edu/islandora/object/edu.ucla.library.specialCollections.losAngelesDailyNews:1185 Photo of William E. MacFaden and Robert W. Kenny (1934)]\n* [https://scocal.stanford.edu/opinion/warner-v-kenny-29323 Stanford University]: Warner v. Kenny\n* [http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n80009886.html Library of Congress]:  Kenny, Robert W. (Robert Walker), 1901-1976\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-legal}}\n{{Succession box |\n  before= [[Earl Warren]]| |\n  title= [[California Attorney General]] |\n  years= 1943&ndash;1947 |\n  after= [[Frederick N. Howser]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Attorneys General of California}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kenny, Robert W}}\n[[Category:California state senators]]\n[[Category:California state court judges]]\n[[Category:California Attorneys General]]\n[[Category:1901 births]]\n[[Category:1976 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American judges]]\n\n{{California-politician-stub}}\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Aboudaqn", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo:  extra carriage return", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_W._Kenny"}
{"title_page": "Calling the World", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Calling the World\n| type       = Studio album\n| artist     = [[Rooney (band)|Rooney]]\n| cover      = Calling_the_world.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = July 17, 2007\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     = Seedy Underbelly,  Big Brown Sound, The Boat, The Pass, Encore Recording Studios and [[Sunset Sound Recorders|Sunset Sound]]\n| genre      = [[Alternative rock]], [[power pop]]\n| length     = 43:54\n| label      = [[Geffen Records|Geffen]]\n| producer   = [[John Fields (producer)|John Fields]]\n| prev_title = [[Rooney (album)|Rooney]]\n| prev_year  = 2003\n| next_title = [[Eureka (Rooney album)|Eureka]]\n| next_year  = 2010\n}}\n\n{{Album ratings\n| MC        = 60/100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/calling-the-world/rooney|title=Calling the World by Rooney|publisher=|accessdate=3 October 2016}}</ref>\n| rev1      = [[Absolutepunk.net]]\n| rev1Score = 89%<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=246550|title=chorus.fm|publisher=|accessdate=3 October 2016}}</ref>\n| rev2      = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1078348|pure_url=yes}}</ref>\n| rev3      = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/artists/rooney/albums/album/15342782/review/15605637/calling_the_world |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-08-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071002032621/http://www.rollingstone.com/artists/rooney/albums/album/15342782/review/15605637/calling_the_world |archivedate=2007-10-02 }}</ref>\n| rev4      = [[stv.tv]]\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stv.tv/content/out/music/album_reviews/display.html?id%3Dopencms%3A%2Fout%2Fmusic%2Falbum_reviews%2FCalling_The_World |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-10-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012164347/http://www.stv.tv/content/out/music/album_reviews/display.html?id=opencms%3A%2Fout%2Fmusic%2Falbum_reviews%2FCalling_The_World |archivedate=2007-10-12 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Calling the World''''' is the second studio album by American [[alternative rock]] band [[Rooney (band)|Rooney]].  It was released on July 17, 2007. \n\nThe album is the result of almost three years of recording, with over 50 songs recorded during the sessions. \"[[When Did Your Heart Go Missing?]]\", was released as the lead single. The album was produced by [[John Fields (producer)|John \"Strawberry\" Fields]]. Rooney unveiled tracks from the album at a series of Monday night concerts in Los Angeles during March. The cover is a recreation of the cover to the [[The Doors (album)|self-titled debut album]] of classic rock band [[The Doors]] and an homage to ''[[Rubber Soul]]'' by the classic rock band [[The Beatles]]. Alternative artwork was used on the album's European release.\n\nFollowing its release, ''Calling the World'' debuted at number 42 on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], selling about 15,000 copies in its first week.<ref>Katie Hasty, [http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1050536/now-25-scores-12th-no-1-album-of-the-series \"'NOW 25' Scores 12th No. 1 Album Of The Series\"], Billboard.com, July 25, 2007.</ref> A second single \"I Should've Been After You\" was released later in the year, while a third single, \"Are You Afraid\" was released in some countries early in 2008.\n\n==Track listing==\nAll songs written and composed by [[Robert Coppola Schwartzman]].\n#\"Calling the World\" \u2013 3:02\n#\"[[When Did Your Heart Go Missing?]]\" \u2013 3:31\n#\"I Should've Been After You\" \u2013 4:23\n#\"Tell Me Soon\" \u2013 3:19\n#\"Don't Come Around Again\" \u2013 4:01\n#\"Are You Afraid?\" \u2013 4:11\n#\"Love Me or Leave Me\" \u2013 3:12\n#\"Paralyzed\" \u2013 2:34\n#\"What For\" \u2013 3:43\n#\"All in Your Head\" \u2013 3:43\n#\"Believe in Me\" \u2013 4:02\n#\"Help Me Find My Way\" \u2013 4:12\n\nThe album came with bonus songs depending on where it was purchased:\n*[[Best Buy]] - \"Get Away\"\n*[[iTunes]] - \"Sleep Song\"\n*[[Target Corporation|Target]] - \"Jump in My Bed\"\n*UK bonus tracks - \"Jump in My Bed\" and \"Get Away\"\n*Japan bonus tracks - all of the above\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Personnel==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Rooney\n*[[Robert Schwartzman]] - [[Lead vocalist|lead vocals]], [[rhythm guitar]], producer\n*Taylor Locke - [[lead guitar]], [[Backing vocalist|backing vocals]]\n*Matthew Winter - [[bass guitar]]\n*[[Ned Brower]] - [[Drum kit|drums]], [[Backing vocalist|backing vocals]]\n*Louie Stephens - [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]], [[piano]]\n\n;Additional musicians\n* [[Richard Dodd]] - cello (tracks 4, 11)\n* Leah Katz - viola (tracks 4, 11)\n* Daphne Chen - violin (tracks 4, 11)\n* [[Eric Gorfain]] - violin (tracks 4, 11)\n* [[The Section Quartet]] - strings (tracks 4, 11)\n* [[Dhani Harrison]] - additional vocals (track 1)\n* [[Andy Sturmer]] - additional vocals (track 3)\n* Ducky Carlisle - tambourine (track 5)\n* Stephen Lu - string arrangement (tracks 1,4)\n{{col-2}}\n;Production\n* [[John Fields (record producer)|John Fields]] \u2013 producer, recording, mixing\n* Ross Hogarth - engineer\n* [[Ted Jensen]] - mastering\n* Alyssa Pittaluga - assistant engineer\n* Andrew Lynch - assistant engineer\n* Atom - assistant engineer\n* Mike Laza - assistant engineer\n* Sara Killion - assistant engineer\n* Scott Elgin - assistant engineer\n* Steven Miller - additional recording \n* [[Woody Jackson]] - additional recording \n* [[Dorian Crozier|Dorian \"Wook\" Crozier]] - drum tech\n* [[Mike Fasano (musician)|Mike Fasano]] - drum tech\n* Kevin Dobski \u2013 management \n* Robert Hayes - management \n* [[Martin Kierszenbaum]] - A&R\n* [[Autumn de Wilde]] - photography\n* Meeno - photography\n* Sasha Eisenman - photography\n* Jan\u00e9e Meadows \u2013 art direction, design\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Calling